		   <br /><nobr><span class="notbold">Score</span>: Decent [3.00]</nobr><br /><br /><a href="/cgi-bin/pm.pl?action=addtolist&addname=Anonymous&type=Address" id="fs8"><img src="/shared/plus.gif" border="0" align="middle" height="9" width="9" alt="Add to address book"> Add to address book</a><br /><img src="/shared/transp.gif" width="135" border="0" height="1"></td><td valign="top" class="mform" width="100%"><p>At your level (I am assuming in the mid-late teens if you are doing the bandits in WK) those druids are just plain nasty!&nbsp;&nbsp;I remember fighting those and it generally was not a good idea to solo them, a friendly druid/cleric/shaman for heals is the best bet, because then you can wade in and not have to worry about their Damage Shields (which hurt us rangers, especially if you are DW).  I always keep a high damage high delay weapon available---and between level 20-30 it was my primary weapon, switching to DW only when I was the primary tank and needed to keep the MOBs glued to me.  If you are after exp, the moral is don't solo!  We aren't Mages or Necros!  Grab a few buddies, pull whites and blues singly or in small numbers, and don't let your casters tell you to wait when they are at 70m...pull constantly all the time, but nothing that will take longer than a minute to kill...if your casters get LOM they can always med out a fight, and if you are doing blues it won't make a signifigant difference.  When you start to get to the upper 20s, though this changes...pull low blues with a smaller group and make sure people are fairly prepped for whites (not necessarily FM, but in the top 25% of their bar)  The key is low risk combats, and lots of them, rather than higher risk combats that can get you killed.  (nothing worse than dieing to slow down your exp gain).<br /><br />Good Luck<br />Senetta Bowangel<br />Mourningstar Guild<br />33 Ranger Luclin</p></td></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2" class="mform"><table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" wi